.\" Manpage for hsh (Holberton Simple Shell)
.TH HSH 1 "Aout 2025" "1.0" "User Commands"


.SH \m[cyan]NAME\m[white]
hsh \- simple UNIX command interpreter


.SH \m[cyan]SYNOPSIS\m[white]
.B \m[yellow]hsh\m[white]
.RI [ command ]
.br
.B \m[yellow]hsh\m[white]
execute a command from the system.


.SH \m[cyan]DESCRIPTION\m[white]
The
.B \m[yellow]hsh\m[white]
program is a simple command-line interpreter.
It mimics basic functionality of a UNIX shell.
.PP
It reads commands from the user or a file, parses them, and executes them by forking processes.
The shell supports:
.IP \[bu] 2
Executing commands found in the system PATH
.IP \[bu] 2
Handling command arguments
.IP \[bu] 2
Simple built-in commands like
.B \m[yellow]exit\m[white]
and
.B \m[yellow]env\m[white]
.IP \[bu] 2
Interactive mode and non-interactive mode


.SH \m[cyan]OPTIONS\m[white]
.TP
.I input_file
A text file containing commands to be executed, one per line.


.SH \m[cyan]BUILTINS\m[white]
The following built-in commands are supported:
.TP
.B \m[yellow]exit\m[white]
Exit the shell.
.TP
.B \m[yellow]env\m[white]
Print the current environment variables.


.SH \m[cyan]EXIT STATUS\m[white]
The
.B \m[yellow]hsh\m[white]
command returns:
.IP 0
If the last executed command was successful.
.IP 1
If an internal shell error occurred.


.SH \m[cyan]EXAMPLES\m[white]
.B \m[yellow]Run in interactive mode:\m[white]
.PP
.EX
$ ./hsh
($) ls -l
($) exit
.EE
.PP
.B \m[yellow]Run in non-interactive mode:\m[white]
.PP
.EX
$ echo "ls -l" | ./hsh
.EE


.SH \m[cyan]FILES\m[white]
.TP
.I AUTHORS
List of individuals who contributed to the project.
.TP
.I /bin/*
System binaries available to execute.
.TP
.I /usr/bin/*
Additional system binaries available to execute.


.SH \m[cyan]ENVIRONMENT\m[white]
The following environment variables affect the behavior of
.B \m[yellow]hsh\m[white]:
.TP
.B PATH
Specifies the directories to search for commands.
.TP
.B HOME
Specifies the default starting directory for the shell.
.TP
.B USER
Current logged-in user.


.SH \m[cyan]AUTHOR\m[white]
See the
.I AUTHORS
file in the project root directory for the list of contributors.


.SH \m[cyan]SEE ALSO\m[white]
.BR bash (1),


